As Naima wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/25/2004 at 13:57:34 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>The fresh Roasted Nut Store wishes to mix nuts that sells for $1.40 
>per pound with nuts that sells for $2.00 per pound.In order to make a 
>mixture that will sell for $1.60 per pound,how many pounds of the $1.
>40 per pound nuts should be mixed with 50 pounds of $2.00 per pound 
>nut?
>
>[Difficulty]
>I find the second part of the question hard to understand,because the 
>second pounds of nuts have already been given in the question.I know 
>how to account for both nuts type questions but am not able not find 
>one type of nuts they have asked for
>
>[Thoughts]
>I have had solved similar questions where it is asked how many 
>quantities of this should be mixed with this to make that much of 
>mixture but not able to solve for a single quantity of mixture.

Hello Naima,

Let x be the number of pounds of the $1.40/lb nuts  to make x+50 pounds of $1.60/lb 
nuts.

The amount of dollars must balance:

(x+50)*1.60 = x*1.40 + 50*2.00.



